            "text": "ROOT",
            "relation": "null"
        },
        {
            "id": 1,
            "parent": 6,
            "text": "Unification grammars are widely accepted as an expressive means ",
            "relation": "BACKGROUND"
        },
        {
            "id": 2,
            "parent": 1,
            "text": "for describing the structure of natural languages . <S>",
            "relation": "ENABLEMENT"
        },
        {
            "id": 3,
            "parent": 1,
            "text": "In general , the recognition problem is undecidable for unification grammars . <S>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 4,
            "parent": 5,
            "text": "Even with restricted variants of the formalism , offline parsable grammars , ",
            "relation": "CONTRAST"
        },
        {
            "id": 5,
            "parent": 3,
            "text": "the problem is computationally hard . <S>",
            "relation": "CAUSE-RESULT-REASON"
        },
        {
            "id": 6,
            "parent": 0,
            "text": "We present two natural constraints on unification grammars ",
            "relation": "ROOT"
        },
        {
            "id": 7,
            "parent": 6,
            "text": "which limit their expressivity . <S>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 8,
            "parent": 9,
            "text": "We first show ",
            "relation": "ATTRIBUTION"
        },
        {
            "id": 9,
            "parent": 6,
            "text": "that non-reentrant unification grammars generate exactly the class of contextfree languages . <S>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 10,
            "parent": 6,
            "text": "We then relax the constraint ",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 11,
            "parent": 12,
            "text": "and show ",
            "relation": "ATTRIBUTION"
        },
        {
            "id": 12,
            "parent": 10,
            "text": "that one-reentrant unification grammars generate exactly the class of tree-adjoining languages . <S>",
            "relation": "CAUSE-RESULT-REASON"
        },
        {
            "id": 13,
            "parent": 6,
            "text": "We thus relate the commonly used and linguistically motivated formalism of unification grammars to more restricted , computationally tractable classes of languages . <S>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        }
    ]
}